            <tr><td class="phase-cell">Motivate</td><td>Decide what to sell, research comparable ads for pricing, look at how others write their listings.</td><td style="color:var(--text-muted);">No significant pain here, this stage flows naturally.</td><td><span class="touchpoint-pill">Homepage</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td class="phase-cell">Post and Check</td><td>Write the listing, customise the description for the specific item, include key information in the title, then monitor clicks and reply rates.</td><td><div class="pain-item">No suitable category for the item</div><div class="pain-item">Photos do not load on relisted ads (server clears images older than six months but never tells sellers)</div><div class="pain-item">Listing duration too short, sellers want more than 30 days</div><div class="pain-item">New ads do not appear at the top of Manage My Ads</div><div class="pain-item">Group ads are difficult to compose and post</div></td><td><span class="touchpoint-pill">Post an Ad UI</span><span class="touchpoint-pill">Ad performance features</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td class="phase-cell">Respond</td><td>Reply promptly to buyer messages, share additional photos, arrange viewings and confirm meetup details.</td><td><div class="pain-item">Irrelevant or off-topic messages from buyers</div><div class="pain-item">Buyers ask for information already in the listing</div><div class="pain-item">Requests for private information (address, bank details)</div><div class="pain-item">Email auto-replies set by sellers are silently dropped and never reach buyers</div></td><td><span class="touchpoint-pill">Messaging system</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td class="phase-cell">Sell</td><td>Meet at agreed location, provide a viewing, hand over the item. Cash is strongly preferred. Some ship low-value or bundled items.</td><td><div class="pain-item">Unreasonable low-ball offers waste time and create friction</div><div class="pain-item">Buyer protection fees and shipping complexity deter sellers from using the service</div></td><td><span class="touchpoint-pill">Shipping service</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td class="phase-cell">Re-post</td><td>Re-list unsold items, reconnect with previous buyers who reach out directly, manage repeat sales relationships.</td><td><div class="pain-item">Re-posting is cumbersome and poorly signposted</div><div class="pain-item">Sellers cannot see reviews they have received, no notification or easy navigation</div></td><td><span class="touchpoint-pill">Reposting UI</span></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-grid">
      <div class="chart-card"><h4>Opportunities for Gumtree, by Priority</h4><div style="position:relative;width:100%;height:280px;"><canvas id="chartOpportunities"></canvas></div></div>
      <div class="info-card"><h4>Key Best Practice Findings from Super Sellers</h4>
        <div class="insight-block"><h5>Creating effective ads</h5><p>High-quality photos with clear backgrounds, key information in the title (price, condition, size), and approachable phrases like "open to reasonable offers" consistently boost click and reply rates. Posting on Fridays and weekends is perceived to generate more responses.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-block gold-border"><h5>Communication that converts</h5><p>Prompt replies, sharing extra photos proactively and maintaining a warm but efficient tone all drive successful outcomes. Sellers who set email auto-replies during unavailable periods do not realise those messages are silently dropped, a gap fixable with a simple platform communication.</p></div>
        <div class="insight-block navy-border"><h5>Safe and smooth transactions</h5><p>In-person, cash transactions are strongly preferred because they feel controlled and final. Sellers need the same level of protection as buyers in shipping scenarios. Buyer protection fees on top of shipping costs are actively deterring sellers from using the service.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CASE 4 -->
  <div class="case-panel" id="case-3">
    <div class="case-header">
      <div>
        <div class="case-title">The Keeper of Paintings, National Gallery AR Experience</div>
        <div class="case-subtitle">Cross-cultural UX research programme for a first-of-its-kind immersive gallery experience · Brunel University London x The National Gallery</div>
        <div class="tags-wrap"><span class="method-tag">Desk Research</span><span class="method-tag">Practitioner Interviews (14)</span><span class="method-tag">Parent Surveys (50)</span><span class="method-tag">Children Focus Groups (24)</span><span class="method-tag">Co-design Workshops</span><span class="method-tag">Field Testing</span></div>
      </div>
      <span class="case-badge">UX Researcher · Brunel · 2019 to 2022</span>
    </div>

    <div class="case-grid">
      <div class="info-card"><h4>The Project</h4><p>A research and development initiative co-led by StoryFutures at Brunel University and The National Gallery, the first time the Gallery had applied digital immersive technology to its on-site visitor experience. Seven institutions from the UK and China collaborated to create a child-friendly experience that worked meaningfully across both markets. My role was to serve as the bridge between the UK and China teams, facilitating mutual understanding of markets, audience behaviour, production workflows and creative goals across two very different institutional cultures.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><h4>Research Questions</h4><ul><li>Which immersive cultural experiences are most successful globally, and what makes them work?</li><li>How do UK and Chinese cultural production teams approach immersive content differently?</li><li>What are the primary interests and preferences of children and families in both countries?</li><li>What type of experience should the National Gallery create to genuinely increase visitor engagement?</li></ul></div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card" style="margin-bottom:1.3rem;">
      <h4>Three Research Phases</h4>
      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:1rem;margin-top:0.8rem;">
        <div style="padding:1.05rem;background:var(--navy-light);border-radius:8px;border:1px solid rgba(26,53,102,0.15);"><div style="font-size:0.66rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.1em;color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:0.35rem;font-weight:600;">Phase 1</div><div style="font-weight:500;color:var(--text);font-size:0.85rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Competitive Landscape</div><div style="font-size:0.77rem;color:var(--text-muted);line-height:1.65;">Desk research on global immersive cultural experiences and practitioner interviews with 14 production experts across the UK and China.</div></div>
        <div style="padding:1.05rem;background:var(--mint-light);border-radius:8px;border:1px solid rgba(26,107,94,0.15);"><div style="font-size:0.66rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.1em;color:var(--mint);margin-bottom:0.35rem;font-weight:600;">Phase 2</div><div style="font-weight:500;color:var(--text);font-size:0.85rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Audience Landscape</div><div style="font-size:0.77rem;color:var(--text-muted);line-height:1.65;">Parent surveys with 50 families exploring children's museum habits and AR familiarity, plus focus groups with 24 children on interests and painting preferences.</div></div>
        <div style="padding:1.05rem;background:var(--gold-light);border-radius:8px;border:1px solid rgba(200,137,10,0.18);"><div style="font-size:0.66rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.1em;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:0.35rem;font-weight:600;">Phase 3</div><div style="font-weight:500;color:var(--text);font-size:0.85rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Design Areas</div><div style="font-size:0.77rem;color:var(--text-muted);line-height:1.65;">Co-design workshops with children to shape the concept, then a field study testing the AR experience through observation, post-session discussion and usability surveys.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-grid">
      <div class="chart-card"><h4>Testing Results, Experience Dimensions</h4><div style="position:relative;width:100%;height:265px;"><canvas id="chartGallery"></canvas></div></div>
      <div>
        <div class="info-card" style="margin-bottom:1rem;"><h4>Key Audience Insights</h4><ul><li style="margin-bottom:0.45rem;">Children in both the UK and China had <strong>limited AR experience but strong enthusiasm</strong> for it once introduced.</li><li style="margin-bottom:0.45rem;">Mobile and tablet games were strongly preferred over PC-based games, informing the decision to build a mobile-first AR experience.</li><li style="margin-bottom:0.45rem;">Art galleries were perceived as less engaging than science museums because of static, non-interactive displays, a direct creative brief.</li><li style="margin-bottom:0.45rem;">Boys were drawn to level progression and rewards; girls preferred avatar customisation. The final concept accommodated both without compromising either.</li></ul></div>
        <div class="info-card"><h4>Cross-Cultural Collaboration Insight</h4><p style="font-size:0.84rem;">UK teams prioritised contracts and research before moving into production. Chinese teams focused more on pre-sales and operated at a faster pace. Bridging these two working cultures required active facilitation of shared creative and strategic goals at every stage and a genuine investment in mutual understanding rather than assuming alignment.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,var(--navy-light),var(--mint-light));border:1px solid rgba(26,53,102,0.15);border-radius:12px;padding:1.8rem;margin-top:1.4rem;">
      <div style="font-size:0.68rem;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--navy);font-weight:600;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Final Concept</div>
      <div style="font-family:'DM Serif Display',serif;font-size:1.45rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;">The Keeper of Paintings</div>
      <p style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.88;max-width:660px;">An interactive, gamified AR mobile app combining progression levels and a reward system. A neutral guide character, the Keeper of Paintings, leads children through an immersive journey to explore and appreciate artworks at the National Gallery. The story begins with the Keeper losing a magical colour palette. Visitors follow clues hidden inside the paintings to recover it, earning rewards along the way and ultimately earning the title of the new Keeper of Paintings.</p>
      <div style="margin-top:1rem;display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:0.4rem;"><span class="hmw-tag navy">Gamified AR mobile experience</span><span class="hmw-tag">Cross-cultural design</span><span class="hmw-tag gold">Child-friendly narrative</span><span class="hmw-tag">Progressive reward system</span><span class="hmw-tag navy">National Gallery launch</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

